First, note that the integral above is improper with a singularity at
$\displaystyle x=1$. Splitting up the integral there, we see that

\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{2} \frac{1}{x^2-1} \ dx &= \int_{0}^{1} \frac{1}{x^2-1} \ dx + \int_{1}^{2} \frac{1}{x^2-1} \ dx\\
&= \lim_{b \to 1^{-}} \int_{0}^{b} \frac{1}{x^2-1} \ dx + \lim_{a \to 1^{+}}\int_{a}^{2} \frac{1}{x^2-1} \ dx\\
\end{align*}

Now, let $\displaystyle \frac{1}{x^2-1} = \frac{A}{x-1} + \frac{B}{x+1}$
by the partial fraction decomposition. We note that \begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1} \frac{1}{x^2-1} \ dx &= \int_{0}^{1} \frac{A}{x-1} \ dx + \int_{0}^{1} \frac{B}{x+1} \ dx
\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1} \frac{A}{x-1} \ dx
\end{align*}

doesn't seem to converge since it behaves like
$\int_{-1}^0 \frac{1}{x} \ dx$, so the whole integral does not converge.
(In particular, we don't even need to worry about what $\displaystyle A$
and $\displaystyle B$ are, since they are non-zero constants!) Let's
prove this rigorously.

\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1} \frac{A}{x-1} \ dx &= A \cdot \lim_{b \to 1^{-}} \int_{0}^{b} \frac{1}{x-1} \ dx \\
&= A \cdot \lim_{b \to 1^{-}}\ln|x-1|_{0}^{b} \\
&= A \cdot \left(\lim_{b \to 1^{-}}\ln|b-1| - \ln|0-1|\right) \\
\end{align*}

Since $\displaystyle \lim_{b \to 1^{-}}\ln|b-1|$ diverges, we have that
the integral diverges and thus the entire integral does not exist.
